item.title: Electronic Billboard System
item.description: Three Java programs (Display, Server and Management System) which work together in a client-server style to allow the displaying, uploading and scheduling of XML-formatted billboards depending on user permissions.

item.title: EQ Explorations
item.description: I helped develop a mobile app for Energy Queensland in a team of four as the final year project at QUT. The purpose of the app was to explore the capabilities of LiDAR, asset identification and asset augmentation on the iPhone 12 Pro to assist field technicians with their tasks. My role on the team was the main developer of the app, so I contributed a significant portion towards its development.

item.title: Bookplanet
item.description: Heroku Deployment A book marketplace produced in a group of four. I created the website’s backend and deployed it with Heroku.

item.title: Stocks Website and Server
item.description: A stock website which interacts via a RESTful API with a backend server to display stock market data and its latest price history in an Angular table. Registration and authentication is also implemented via an SQL database and JSON Web Tokens. Authenticated users can view a stock’s full price history in a table and a graph.

item.title: Machine Learning
item.description: I used a number of suitable frameworks to create Jupyter notebooks for the tasks of image classification, person re-identification and semantic person search. For the final group project, we compared the use of Dense SIFT and a Bag of Words fed into an SVM ensemble and Random Forest vs a traditional VGG network for image classification. I was responsible for developing the Python script/notebook and leading the group for the report.

item.title: Car Park Simulation
item.description: A car park simulation system created in a group of four people. I was the main developer and took responsibility for creating the simulator, fire alarm system (safety critical) and parts of the manager. This project greatly improved my understanding of threading, synchronisation primitives and shared memory.
